🔷 1. Association (The Base Concept)
👉 What is it?

Association = “uses-a” or “knows-a” relationship

Two classes are related, but no ownership.

🧠 Think:

“They are connected, but can exist independently.”

💡 Example:

A Teacher and Student

A teacher teaches students

A student exists even without a specific teacher

class Student {}

class Teacher {
    List<Student> students;  // association
}
Key Points:

No lifecycle dependency

No ownership

Just a reference

🔷 2. Aggregation (Weak Association)
👉 What is it?

Aggregation = “has-a” (but weak ownership)

One object contains another, but:

The contained object can exist independently

🧠 Think:

“Whole–part, but parts can live without the whole.”

💡 Example:

A Department has Employees

If department is deleted → employees still exist

class Employee {}

class Department {
    List<Employee> employees;  // aggregation
}
Key Points:

Weak ownership

Lifecycle is independent

Often shared objects

🔷 3. Composition (Strong Association)
👉 What is it?

Composition = “owns-a” (strong ownership)

One object completely owns another.

🧠 Think:

“If the whole dies, the part dies.”

💡 Example:

A House has Rooms

If house is destroyed → rooms are gone

class Room {}

class House {
    private List<Room> rooms = new ArrayList<>();

    House() {
        rooms.add(new Room()); // created inside
    }
}
Key Points:

Strong ownership

Lifecycle tied together

No sharing

Usually created inside parent

🔥 The Ultimate Comparison (This is what you remember)
Concept	Relationship	Ownership	Lifecycle	Example
Association	uses-a	❌ None	Independent	Teacher–Student
Aggregation	has-a	⚠️ Weak	Independent	Department–Employee
Composition	owns-a	✅ Strong	Dependent	House–Room
🧠 Golden Memory Trick (Never Forget This)

Think of 3 levels of attachment:

1️⃣ Association → “I know you”

Casual connection

2️⃣ Aggregation → “I have you”

But you can leave anytime

3️⃣ Composition → “You are part of me”

You cannot exist without me

🔥 Interview-Level Insight (VERY IMPORTANT)

Most people fail here 👇

❗ Java DOES NOT enforce aggregation vs composition

Java only has references.

👉 The difference is:

How you design

Who creates the object

Who controls lifecycle

✔️ This is Aggregation:
class Department {
    List<Employee> employees;

    Department(List<Employee> employees) {
        this.employees = employees; // passed from outside
    }
}

👉 Employees created outside → weak relationship

✔️ This is Composition:
class House {
    private List<Room> rooms;

    House() {
        rooms = new ArrayList<>();
        rooms.add(new Room()); // created internally
    }
}

👉 Rooms created inside → strong ownership

⚠️ Common Mistake

❌ “If I use new, it's composition”

👉 Not always.

What matters:

Can object exist outside?

Is it shared?

Who controls lifecycle?

🧠 Final Mental Model (Burn this in)
Association  → Just linked
Aggregation  → Contains (loosely)
Composition  → Owns (tightly)
